				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Readers Respond: On âWorkers Betrayed by Visa Loopholesâ</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Marie Tessier			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-06-16T20:20:54+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 16, 2015 4:20 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 16, 2015 4:20 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/06/16/readers-respond-on-workers-betrayed-by-visa-loopholes/" data-title="Readers Respond: On âWorkers Betrayed by Visa Loopholesâ" data-description="Workers, entrepreneurs, and others illustrated the complexity of the immigration reform debate with their responses to an editorial.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/16/opinion/16tessierWEB2/16tessierWEB2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/16/opinion/16tessierWEB2/16tessierWEB2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/16/opinion/16tessierWEB2/16tessierWEB2-blog480.jpg" id="100000003745127" width="480" height="320" alt="The Team Disney building in Lake Buena Vista, Fla."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The Team Disney building in Lake Buena Vista, Fla.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Brian Blanco for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">American workers, entrepreneurs, immigrants and a few readers supporting big employers illustrated the complexity of the immigration reform debate with their responses to an <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/15/opinion/workers-betrayed-by-visa-loopholes.html">editorial</a> about abuses in a high-tech visa program.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âImmigration policy should not undermine Americansâ jobs, wages or working conditions,â the editorial board wrote. âThe problem is that what some companies want â cheap, exploitable, disposable labor â is exactly what the system can be twisted into giving them.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The editorial addressed two recent major instances, at Walt Disney World in Orlando and at Southern California Edison, in which companies laid off hundreds of technology workers and replaced them with lower-paid foreign workers via outsourcing firms in India. These workers entered the country under the H-1B visa program that was meant to allow companies to recruit abroad for jobs they were not able to fill with American workers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAmericans have known about H-1B visa abuses for years,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/15/opinion/workers-betrayed-by-visa-loopholes.html?comments#permid=15223394">wrote Jeffrey in Massachusetts</a>, who said he had lost his own job. âThe administration and Congress both have been aware of the problems, but the issue has been buried under the mounds of money coming from the tech industry.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many readers argued that the United States has plenty of highly educated workers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI know too many underemployed U.S. students in STEM fields and laid off older workers in computer science and engineering to believe that we donât have good workers here,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/15/opinion/workers-betrayed-by-visa-loopholes.html?comments#permid=15223323">Nancy Darling in Oberlin, Ohio, wrote</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Large companies like Disney and Southern California Edison should respect the market forces that place a premium on high-tech wage rates, some readers said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThat we need to import foreign workers to fill a skills shortage is absurd because it defies the basic underpinnings of American capitalism,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/15/opinion/workers-betrayed-by-visa-loopholes.html?comments#permid=15226386">John Coffey in Georgia wrote</a>. âSend the H-1B workers home and you will see a flood of highly qualified, home-grown Americans going back to work.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Several high-technology visa holders wrote to say the immigration system ill serves both the United States economy and highly skilled would-be immigrants.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI am an Indian and spent close to 10 years spinning through the H-1B and immigration circus,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/15/opinion/workers-betrayed-by-visa-loopholes.html?comments#permid=15224616">V in Philadelphia wrote</a>. âThe fact is that when I left India to pursue a masterâs degree, I had full intentions to pursue a long career in the U.S.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe need to a solution that separates candidates who want to immigrate and will add value to the country from candidates who are intended to be used for temporary staff.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A bipartisan effort in Congress would tighten eligibility rules, give workers more access to job openings, require better pay and give federal investigators more power to investigate abuses, the editorial board wrote.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A number of readers endorsed reforms that would bring the program back in line with its creatorsâ intentions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAs an educator and an entrepreneur, I may be in the minority defending H-1B, but that visa proved crucial in starting two tech companies, which hired more U.S. Citizens than H-1B visa holders, but needed both to survive,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/15/opinion/workers-betrayed-by-visa-loopholes.html?comments#permid=15226057">J. Carbonell in Pittsburgh wrote</a>. âThe right policy is to reform, not to reduce or eliminate.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some readers said American technology workers should face facts about global wages.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAmerican programmers routinely demand compensation which exceeds five digits. Foreign specialists are more realistic, more flexible, and typically work harder,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/15/opinion/workers-betrayed-by-visa-loopholes.html?comments#permid=15226450">Vizitei Yuri in Columbia, Mo., wrote</a>. âIn a world of global, integrated commerce, artificial barriers to the tendency for economic disparities to equalize will simply not work.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some said solutions need to address such a global market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âA casual look at all the âbusiness process outsourcingâ jobs posted around the world shows that a very large number of these jobs are being off-shored,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/15/opinion/workers-betrayed-by-visa-loopholes.html?comments#permid=15224156">Ben P. in Austin, Texas</a>, wrote. âTo blame the H-1B program for these job losses entirely misses the broader picture.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And in a theme that is familiar across comments on the United States economy, many readers remarked on the intersection between power and money in Washington, D.C.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âOur H-1B program is allowing Congress to disempower educated, hard-working Americans,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/15/opinion/workers-betrayed-by-visa-loopholes.html?comments#permid=15223570">Springtime in Boston wrote</a>. âThis is not a democracy, itâs an auction.â</p>
	</div>
